      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is grounded in the legal principle of democratic legitimacy, arguing that the Constitution represents the will of the people and their elected representatives, not the personal preferences of unelected judges. It relies on the textualist argument that the Constitution is a fixed legal document, and allowing judges to redefine its meaning based on modern values effectively grants them the power to make new laws, which violates the separation of powers. This approach ensures stability and predictability in the law by anchoring judicial decisions to the specific understanding of the text at the time of its ratification.",
